Definition 3.15. We call the natural enhancement of $\mathsf{D}_{\alpha}(\mathcal{C})$ via the enhancement $\boldsymbol{\mathsf{D}}(\mathcal{C})$ of $\mathsf{D}(\mathcal{C})$ the $\alpha$-cocontinuous derived dg category of $\mathcal{C}$. We will denote it by $\boldsymbol{\mathsf{D}}_{\alpha}(\mathcal{C})$.
Definition 4.8. We will call $\mathcal{N}_{\mathcal{A}}\boxtimes_{\mathrm{Cl}}\mathcal{N}_{\mathcal{B}}$ the tensor product of classes of objects $\mathcal{N}_{\mathcal{A}}$ and $\mathcal{N}_{\mathcal{B}}$.
Definition 3.3. Consider $\mathcal{H}\subseteq H^{0}(\mathcal{B})$ and $B\in\mathcal{B}$. A filtration of $B$ consists of a countable collection $(X_{i})_{i=0}^{\infty}$ of objects in $H^{0}(\mathcal{B})$ with $X_{0}=0$ and maps $x_{i}:X_{i}\longrightarrow X_{i+1}$ for all $i\geq 0$ such that $\mathrm{hocolim}(X_{i})=B$. A filtration $(X_{i})_{i=0}^{\infty}$ of $B$ is called an $\mathcal{H}$-filtration if the cone of each $x_{i}:X_{i}\longrightarrow X_{i+1}$ belongs to $\mathcal{H}$ and in this case $B$ is called $\mathcal{H}$-filtered.
Definition 2.4. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a dg $\mathfrak{U}$-category. (1) Let $\alpha$ be a cardinal. We say that $\mathcal{C}$ is homotopically $\alpha$-cocomplete if $H^{0}(\mathcal{A})$ has all $\alpha$-small coproducts. (2) We say that $\mathcal{C}$ is homotopically cocomplete if $\mathcal{C}$ is homotopically $|\mathfrak{U}|$-cocomplete, that is, $H^{0}(\mathcal{A})$ has all $\mathfrak{U}$-small coproducts.
Definition 3.12. [21, ยง6] Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a homotopically $\alpha$-cocomplete small dg category. The $\alpha$-cocontinuous derived category $\mathsf{D}_{\alpha}(\mathcal{C})$ is defined as the full subcategory of $\mathsf{D}(\mathcal{C})$ with objects given by the dg functors $X$ such that for every $\alpha$-small family of objects $\{A_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ the canonical morphism $H^{n}(X)\left(\coprod_{i}^{H^{0}(\mathcal{C})}A_{i}\right)\longrightarrow\prod% _{i}H^{n}(X)(A_{i})$ is invertible for all $n\in\mathbb{Z}$, where $\underset{i}{\overset{H^{0}(\mathcal{C})}{\coprod}}A_{i}$ denotes the coproduct taken in $H^{0}(\mathcal{C})$.
Definition 4.4. Consider $\mathcal{N}_{\mathcal{A}}$ a class of objects in $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{N}_{\mathcal{B}}$ a class of objects in $\mathcal{B}$. With the same notations as above, we say $F\in\mathrm{RHom}(\mathcal{A}\otimes^{\mathrm{L}}\mathcal{B},\mathcal{C})$ biannihilates $(\mathcal{N}_{\mathcal{A}},\mathcal{N}_{\mathcal{B}})$ provided that every $F_{A}$ annihilates $\mathcal{N}_{\mathcal{B}}$ and every $F_{B}$ annihilates $\mathcal{N}_{\mathcal{A}}$.
Definition 3.1. A pretriangulated dg category $\mathcal{A}$ is called well generated if the homotopy category $H^{0}(\mathcal{A})$ is a well generated triangulated category. It is called $\alpha$-compactly generated for some cardinal $\alpha$ if $H^{0}(\mathcal{A})$ is $\alpha$-compactly generated.
Definition 4.16. With the notations above, we put $\mathcal{W}_{\mathfrak{a}}\boxtimes\mathcal{W}_{\mathfrak{b}}=\langle\mathcal{% W}_{\mathfrak{a}}\boxtimes_{\mathrm{Cl}}\mathcal{W}_{\mathfrak{b}}\rangle.$
Definition 3.7. Given two pretriangulated dg categories $\mathcal{A}$, $\mathcal{B}$ and two right quasi-representable functors $F\in\mathrm{RHom}(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B})$, $G\in\mathrm{RHom}(\mathcal{B},\mathcal{A})$, we say that $F$ is left quasi-adjoint to $G$ if and only if $H^{0}(F)\dashv H^{0}(G)$. In this case we write $F\dashv_{H^{0}}G$.
Definition 2.5. Consider dg $\mathfrak{U}$-categories $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$. (1) Let $\alpha$ be a cardinal. A quasi-functor $F\in\mathrm{RHom}(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B})$ is called $\alpha$-cocontinuous if the induced functor $H^{0}(F):H^{0}(\mathcal{A})\longrightarrow H^{0}(\mathcal{B})$ preserves all $\alpha$-small coproducts. We let $\mathrm{RHom}_{\alpha}(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B})\subseteq\mathrm{RHom}(\mathcal% {A},\mathcal{B})$ denote the full dg subcategory of $\alpha$-cocontinuous quasi-functors. (2) A quasi-functor $F\in\mathrm{RHom}(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B})$ is called cocontinuous if it is $|\mathfrak{U}|$-cocontinuous, that is if the induced functor $H^{0}(F):H^{0}(\mathcal{A})\longrightarrow H^{0}(\mathcal{B})$ preserves all $\mathfrak{U}$-small coproducts. We put $\mathrm{RHom}_{\mathsf{c}}(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B})=\mathrm{RHom}_{|\mathfrak{% U}|}(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B}).$
Definition 4.1. Let $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ be well generated dg categories. A well generated tensor product of $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ is defined as a well generated dg category $\mathcal{A}\boxtimes\mathcal{B}$ such that for every well generated dg category $\mathcal{C}$, the following universal property holds: $\mathrm{RHom}_{\mathsf{c}}(\mathcal{A}\boxtimes\mathcal{B},\mathcal{C})\cong% \mathrm{RHom}_{\mathsf{c}}(\mathcal{A},\mathrm{RHom}_{\mathsf{c}}(\mathcal{B},% \mathcal{C})).$
Definition 1.1 A $C$-algebra $A$ constitutes a continuous field of $C^{*}$-algebras if for every $A$ the norm function $\mathrm{spec}~{}C\ni p\mapsto\|a\|_{A_{p}}$ is continuous. $\blacklozenge$
Definition 1.2 A filtration on $G$ is a family of finite-index normal subgroups $N_{\alpha}\trianglelefteq G$ with trivial intersection. Let $H\leq G$ be a subgroup. A filtration $\{N_{\alpha}\}$ of $G$ is an $H$-filtration provided $\bigcap_{\alpha}HN_{\alpha}=H.$ $\blacklozenge$
Definition 4.3. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a modular category and $N={\operatorname{ord}\,}(T_{\mathcal{C}})$. We define the central charge function $\Psi_{\mathcal{C}}\in\mathcal{U}_{\infty}$ of $\mathcal{C}$ as follows: for any ${\sigma}\in{\operatorname{Gal}}(\overline{{\mathbb{Q}}})$, if ${\sigma}|_{{\mathbb{Q}}_{N}}={\sigma}_{k}$, then $\Psi_{\mathcal{C}}({\sigma}):=\xi_{k}(\mathcal{C})\,.$
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a fusion category. We define the signature ${\varepsilon}_{\mathcal{C}}$ of $\mathcal{C}$ as ${\varepsilon}(\sqrt{\operatorname{FPdim}(\mathcal{C})})$ and the categorical dimension signature ${{\varepsilon}_{\mathcal{C}}^{\prime}}$ of $\mathcal{C}$ as ${\varepsilon}({\sqrt{\dim(\mathcal{C})}})$.
Definition 3.7. We call the group homomorphism $I_{\mathcal{E}}:\mathcal{W}(\mathcal{E})\rightarrow\mathcal{U}_{2}$ defined in Theorem 3.4 the $\mathcal{E}$-signature on $\mathcal{W}(\mathcal{E})$, and $I_{\mathcal{E}}([\mathcal{C}])$ the $\mathcal{E}$-signature of $[\mathcal{C}]$. For $\mathcal{E}={\operatorname{Vec}}$ or $\operatorname{sVec}$, we call the group homomorphism ${I_{\mathcal{E}}^{\prime}}:\mathcal{W}(\mathcal{E})\rightarrow\mathcal{U}_{2}$ defined in Theorem 3.5 the categorical dimension $\mathcal{E}$-signature on $\mathcal{W}(\mathcal{E})$, and ${I_{\mathcal{E}}^{\prime}}([\mathcal{C}])$ the categorical dimension $\mathcal{E}$-signature of $[\mathcal{C}]$.
Definition 4.5. Let $\mathcal{W}_{{\operatorname{un}}}$ be the subgroup of $\mathcal{W}$ generated by the pseudounitary modular categories. The function $\Psi:\mathcal{W}_{{\operatorname{un}}}\rightarrow\mathcal{U}_{\infty}$, called the central charge homomorphism, is defined by $\Psi([\mathcal{C}])=\Psi_{\mathcal{C}}$ for any pseudounitary modular category $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 3.7 (Isomorphism of topological correspondences). Let $(X,\lambda)$ and $(X^{\prime},\lambda^{\prime})$ be topological correspondences from $(G,\alpha)$ to $(H,\beta)$. An isomorphism $(X,\lambda,\Delta)\to(X^{\prime},\lambda^{\prime},\Delta^{\prime})$ is a $G$-$H$-equivariant homeomorphism $\phi:X\rightarrow X^{\prime}$ with $\phi_{*}(\lambda)\sim\lambda^{\prime}$.
Definition 2.14 (Morphisms of bicategories, [Benabou1967Bicategories]*Definition 4.1). Let $\mathfrak{S}$ and $\mathfrak{S}^{\prime}$ be bicategories. A morphism $\mathfrak{V}=(V,v)$ from $\mathfrak{S}$ to $\mathfrak{S}^{\prime}$ consists of: i) a map $V\colon\mathfrak{S}_{0}\rightarrow\mathfrak{S}^{\prime}_{0}$ sending an object $A$ to $V(A)$; ii) a family of functors $V(A,B)\colon\mathfrak{S}(A,B)\rightarrow\mathfrak{S}^{\prime}(V(A),V(B))$ sending a 1-cell $S$ to $V(A)$ and a 2-cell $s$ to $V(s)$; iii) for each object $A$ of $\mathfrak{S}$, a 2-cell $v_{A}\in\mathfrak{S}(V(A),V(B))$ $v_{A}\colon I_{V(A)}\Rightarrow V(I_{A});$ iv) a family of natural transformations $v(A,B,C)\colon c(V(A),V(B),V(C))\circ(V(A,B)\times V(B,C))\rightarrow V(A,C)% \circ c(A,B,C).$ If $(S,T)$ is an object of $\mathfrak{S}(A,B)\times\mathfrak{S}^{\prime}(B,C)$, the $(S,T)$-components of $v(A,B,C)$ $v(A,B,C)(S,T)\colon V(S)\circ V(T)\Rightarrow V(S\circ T)$ shall be abbreviated $v$ or $v(S,T)$. This data satisfies the following coherence conditions: v) If $(S,T,U)$ is an object of $\mathfrak{S}(A,B)\times\mathfrak{S}(B,C)\times\mathfrak{S}(C,D)$ the diagram in Figure 2 is commutative. vi) If $S$ is an object of $\mathfrak{S}(A,B)$ then the diagram in Figure 3, for the right identity commutes. A similar diagram for the left identity commutes.
Definition 2.9 (Composite). Let $(X,\alpha)\colon(G_{1},\chi_{1})\rightarrow(G_{2},\chi_{2})\quad\text{ and }% \quad(Y,\beta)\colon(G_{2},\chi_{2})\rightarrow(G_{3},\chi_{3})$ be topological correspondences with $\Delta_{1}$ and $\Delta_{2}$ as the adjoining function, respectively. A composite of these correspondences $(\Omega,\mu):(G_{1},\chi_{1})\rightarrow(G_{3},\chi_{3})$ is defined by: i) the space $\Omega\mathrel{\vcentcolon=}(X\times_{{G_{2}}^{(0)}}Y)/G_{2}$, ii) a family of measures $\mu=\{\mu_{u}\}_{u\in{{G}^{(0)}}_{3}}$ that lifts to $\{b(\alpha\times\beta_{u})\}_{u\in{{G_{3}}^{(0)}}}$ on $Z$ for a cochain $b\in\mathrm{C}^{0}_{G_{3}}((X\times_{{G_{2}}^{(0)}}Y)\rtimes G_{2},\mathbb{R}_% {+}^{*})$ satisfying $d^{0}(b)=D$ where $D\colon(X\times_{{G_{2}}^{(0)}}Y)\rtimes G_{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{*}_{+}$ is $D((x,y),\gamma)=\Delta_{2}(\gamma^{-1},y)$.
